  <h1>
   colour_get_hue
  </h1>
  This function will return the hue of the given colour. This is the "pure" colour tone which is part of the hue, saturation and value (luminosity) method for defining a colour. The following image illustrates how this value corresponds to the
    HSV scale of colour:
  <br/><img src="https://gms.magecorn.com/Manual/assets/Images/Scripting_Reference/GML/Reference/Drawing/get_hue.png"/><br/>
  <h4>
   Syntax:
  </h4>
  <pre><code class="language-gml">colour_get_hue(col);
</code></pre>
  <table>
   <tbody>
    <tr>
     <th>
      Argument
     </th>
     <th>
      Type
     </th>
     <th>
      Description
     </th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      col
     </td>
     <td>
      <span>
       <a href="../../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Reference/Drawing/Colour_And_Alpha/Colour_And_Alpha.htm">
        Colour
       </a>
      </span>
     </td>
     <td>
      The colour to check
     </td>
    </tr>
   </tbody>
  </table>
  <h4>
   Returns:
  </h4>
  <pre><code class="language-gml"><a href="../../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Overview/Data_Types.htm">
 Real
</a></code></pre>
  <h4>
   Example:
  </h4>
  <pre><code class="language-gml">col = merge_colour(colour_get_hue(c_teal), c_white, 0.5);
</code></pre>
  The above code gets the hue used to make the colour constant "c_teal" and then merges it with white at a 50:50 ratio, storing the resulting colour in the variable "col".
